<article>
    <h1>10 shows to catch in Sep&#xAD;tem&#xAD;ber</h1>
    <h2>These in&#xAD;clude South Korean ro&#xAD;mance dra&#xAD;mas, a cook&#xAD;ing series, ori&#xAD;gin sto&#xAD;ries of well-known char&#xAD;ac&#xAD;ters and a lim&#xAD;ited series with big Hol&#xAD;ly&#xAD;wood names</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200827/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-27"><time>2020-08-27</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE / TELEVISION</span>
        - <span role="byline">jan&#xAD;lee@sph.com.sg Jan Lee</span>
    </section>

    <p>1</p>
    <p>YOUNG WALLANDER</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres on Sept 3 on Net­flix</p>
    <p>This new Nordic noir crime series fol­lows a young Kurt Wallander, the most no­table char­ac­ter cre­ated by Swedish nov­el­ist Hen­ning Mankell.</p>
    <p>The ori­gin story of the trou­bled de­tec­tive, played by Adam Pals­son (right), tells how as a rookie cop, he was fast-tracked to be­come a de­tec­tive as he be­gins in­ves­ti­gat­ing his first case – an in­cen­di­ary hate crime.</p>
    <p>2</p>
    <p>THE PAIKFATHER</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres at 11.45am on Sept 5 on Oh!K (StarHub TV Chan­nel 816 and Sing­tel TV Chan­nel 525)</p>
    <p>In this cook­ing show, vet­eran chef and tele­vi­sion per­son­al­ity Paik Jong-won (left, in black)helps rookie chefs come into their own right, by teach­ing them the ba­sics, such as how to fry an egg.</p>
    <p>A large pool of par­tic­i­pants take part in Paik’s lessons over video calls.</p>
    <p>3</p>
    <p>RAISED BY WOLVES</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres on Sept 3 ex­clu­sively on HBO Go</p>
    <p>Os­car-nom­i­nated di­rec­tor Ri­d­ley Scott (Thelma & Louise, 1991) helms this new sci­ence-fic­tion series about two an­droids named</p>
    <p>Mother and Fa­ther (played by Amanda Collin and Abubakar Salim, both above) who are rais­ing hu­man chil­dren on a mys­te­ri­ous planet. Clash­ing reli­gious be­liefs soon lead to con­flicts and the an­droids have to learn to pro­tect their own way of life.</p>
    <p>4</p>
    <p>RATCHED</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres on Sept 18 on Net­flix</p>
    <p>Showrun­ner Ryan Mur­phy, best known for works like Glee (2009 to 2015) and Amer­i­can Hor­ror Story (2011 to present), has de­vel­oped an ori­gin story for Nurse Mil­dred</p>
    <p>Ratched, an asy­lum nurse and an­tag­o­nist in the 1962 novel and 1975 film One Flew Over The Cuckoo’s Nest.</p>
    <p>Ac­tress Sarah Paul­son (above), a long-time col­lab­o­ra­tor of Mur­phy, stars as the tit­u­lar char­ac­ter in this pre­quel.</p>
    <p>5</p>
    <p>RECORD OF YOUTH</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres on Sept 7 on Net­flix</p>
    <p>This much-an­tic­i­pated ro­mance drama fol­lows a pair of child­hood friends who are mod­els seek­ing to make it big as ac­tors, played by lead­ing men Byeon Woo-seok (above, left) and Park Bo-gum (above, right).</p>
    <p>At work, they meet a bud­ding make-up artist, played by Park So-dam (Par­a­site, 2019, above, cen­tre).</p>
    <p>The trio, who come from dif­fer­ent back­grounds, weather the tri­als and tribulatio­ns of youth to­gether.</p>
    <p>6</p>
    <p>DO YOU LIKE BRAHMS</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres at 8.10pm on Tues­day on One (StarHub TV Chan­nel 823/124 and Sing­tel TV Chan­nel 513/604); also avail­able on Viu</p>
    <p>In this youth­ful mu­si­cal ro­mance, a piano prodigy Joon-young, played by up-and-com­ing K-drama star Kim Min-jae (Dr. Ro­man­tic, 2016, above), meets vi­o­lin en­thu­si­ast Song-ah, played by Park Eun-bin (hit drama Hot Stove League, 2019), when they en­rol in col­lege as mu­sic ma­jors.</p>
    <p>7</p>
    <p>LIE AF­TER LIE</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres on Sept 5 on Viu</p>
    <p>This twisty melo­dra­matic ro­mance kicks off with Eun-soo (Lee Yoo-ri) mar­ry­ing into a wealthy fam­ily.</p>
    <p>But when her hus­band dies, she is blamed for it and has to give birth to their baby girl in prison.</p>
    <p>When she is re­leased, she searches for her daugh­ter, who has been adopted by a man named Ji-min.</p>
    <p>She pre­tends to fall in love with him in a bid to marry him and re­unite with her daugh­ter.</p>
    <p>8</p>
    <p>HIKARU NO GO</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres on Sept 21 on iQiyi</p>
    <p>The Chi­nese drama is adapted from a pop­u­lar Ja­panese manga series based on the board game Go.</p>
    <p>It is about a boy Hikaru, who dis­cov­ers a haunted old Go board pos­sessed by the spirit of Fu­ji­wara-no-Sai, a Go player from the Heian era. The boy later be­comes in­ter­ested in the game.</p>
    <p>The Chi­nese adap­ta­tion stars Hu Xianxu (Old Boy, 2018) and Zhang Chao (Some­where Only We Know, 2019).</p>
    <p>9</p>
    <p>TEHRAN</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres on Sept 25 on Ap­ple TV+</p>
    <p>The thrilling new series tells the story of a fe­male Mos­sad (Is­raeli in­tel­li­gence) agent, played by Is­raeli ac­tress Niv Sul­tan (above), who goes un­der­cover on a dan­ger­ous mis­sion in Te­heran, Iran, plac­ing her and ev­ery­one around her in jeop­ardy.</p>
    <p>The es­pi­onage drama counts Moshe Zon­der, writer of Is­raeli tele­vi­sion series Fauda (2015 to present), as an ex­ec­u­tive pro­ducer.</p>
    <p>10</p>
    <p>THE THIRD DAY</p>
    <p>Pre­mieres at 9am on Sept 15 on HBO Go and HBO (StarHub TV Chan­nel 601 and Sing­tel TV Chan­nel 420)</p>
    <p>Star­ring crit­i­cally ac­claimed stars Jude Law and Naomie Har­ris (above), the six-part lim­ited series is told in two parts.</p>
    <p>The first three episodes, themed “Sum­mer”, fol­lows Sam (Law), who is drawn to a mys­te­ri­ous is­land, where its in­hab­i­tants har­bour se­crets, tra­di­tions and trau­mas.</p>
    <p>In the re­main­ing episodes, a woman (Har­ris) ar­rives on the is­land at a dif­fer­ent time and sparks con­flict.</p>

